Tinderbox-ng is now just essentially a script that takes a stage3, adds prolog, kernel sources, portage-ng and copies in a few configuration files. 

For each package in the manifest list (packages to be build), it layers an overlayfs over the modifed stage3 baseline and calls a package manager to build the target. This is a "session".

A few directories inside each "session" are shared across sessions: 

- the ccache, for speeding up compiles
- distfiles, to prevent redownloading of the same file
- binpkg, to store compiled packages, avoiding rebuilding them when they appear in another session as a dependency

Once done, it copies out a few logs that we wants to keep. 

Tinderbox-ng ships with a number of scripts that allow comparison of those logs: 

- did emerge produce the same plan as portage-ng 
- how fast was each stage
- are there any deviations in the installed files. 

This allows for generation of reports. 


No rocket science, but very important to be able to ensure a portage-ng does its job. 

Here's what I want to do conceptually: 

- portage-ng already knows how to advertise its services using bonjour
- portage-ng could reason about stages, overlays, if only it had a repository containing the knowledge
- portage-ng already has an explain system and can even call llm to write human understandable explanations, or help debugging issues
- portage-ng already has a jobserver, with distributed workers (for distributed proving)
- portage-ng already understands transactions (think creating an overlay for new merge transactions)

If we put everything together I believe it would be quite straightforward to ship portage-ng with bootstrap knowledge, enabling it to understand what a stage is, or set up one or more sessions to test "transactions".

We have already proven that portage-ng phas a planning correctness exceeding 100% (it produces plans there where emerge cannot)
We are now doing the same with tinderbox-ng (testing at least 100% build correctness).
Once this is done, we start integration in portage-ng.